right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aClick and Kin is an interdisciplinary examination of how our increasingly mobile and networked age is changing the experience of kinship and connection. Focusing on how identity formation is affected by quick media such as instant messaging, video chat, and social networks, the contributors to this collection use ethnographic and textual analyses, as well as autobiographical approaches, to demonstrate the ways in which the ability to communicate across national boundaries is transforming how we grow together and apart as families, communities, and nations.The essays in Click and Kin span the globe, examining transnational connections that touch in the United States, Canada, Mexico, India, Pakistan, and elsewhere. Together, they offer a unique reflection on the intersection of new media, identity politics, and kinship in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aKinshipxSocial aspects. 0aSocial media. 0aTransborder ethnic groupsxSocial conditions. 0aTransnationalismxSocial aspects. 7aTechnology & Engineering / Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 aAtay, Ahmet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe, Aparajita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, May, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, May, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcKee, Kimberly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoinuddin, Shekh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNg, Isabella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aObermayr, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchultermandl, Silvia, econtributor.4ctb4https:/